SYCHIATRIC SYMPTOMS,,3\r\n2073,SENILE PLAQUES,\"Senile plaques are pathological deposits found in the brains of individuals with Alzheimer's disease. These plaques are primarily composed of amyloid-beta protein and serve as significant markers of the disease. Their presence is closely associated with neuronal damage, which contributes to the cognitive impairment and decline observed in Alzheimer's patients. Overall, senile plaques play a critical role in the progression and pathology of Alzheimer's disease.\",2\r\n2072,NEUROFIBRILLARY TANGLES,\"Neurofibrillary tangles are pathological structures characterized by abnormal accumulations of tau protein within neurons. These tangles are a hallmark of Alzheimer's disease and play a significant role in the progression of the condition. Their presence leads to neuronal dysfunction and eventual cell death, which contributes to the cognitive decline observed in Alzheimer's disease patients. Thus, neurofibrillary tangles are a critical feature in the pathology and symptomatology of this neurodegenerative disorder.\",2\r\n2075,CHOLINE ACETYLTRANSFERASE,\"Choline acetyltransferase is an enzyme significantly reduced in Alzheimer's Disease, leading to decreased acetylcholine levels, which is associated with memory and cognitive impairments.\",2\r\n2088,DONEPEZIL,\"Donepezil, also known by its brand name Aricept, is an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor primarily used to treat Alzheimer's Disease. It has been approved by the FDA for this purpose. Donepezil works by inhibiting the breakdown of acetylcholine, a neurotransmitter involved in memory and learning, thereby improving cognitive function in patients with Alzheimer's Disease. Additionally, it is used to enhance cognitive function in patients with Vascular Dementia (VD), a condition characterized by cognitive decline due to reduced blood flow to the brain. Overall, Donepezil is a widely recognized medication for managing cognitive impairments associated with neurodegenerative and